-- French Stocks Advance: Dassault Systemes, Peugeot, Vallourec Lead Gains
-- Adam Haigh
-- 2010-06-28T16:34:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-28/french-stocks-advance-bourbon-peugeot-citroen-vallourec-lead-the-gains.html

          
          
             The CAC 40 climbed 56.72, or 1.6
percent, to 3,576.45. The SBF 120 Index advanced 1.5 percent.  
 The following are among the most active stocks traded in
France today.  
 Dassault Systemes SA  (DSY FP) surged 2.4 percent to 51.01
euros, ending the longest streak of declines since May 7. The
company, whose software is used to design cars and aircraft, was
raised to “overweight” from “neutral” at HSBC Holdings Plc.  
 Imerys SA  (NK FP) rose 2.4 percent to 44.37 euros, the
first gain in four days. AlphaValue SAS upgraded the shares to
“add” from “sell.”  
 PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP) gained 2.8 percent to 22.3
euros, ending the longest streak of declines in a month. The
carmaker has lifted its 2010 sales target for the DS3 model to
70,000 from 45,000, La Lettre de L’Expansion reported, without
citing anyone.  
 Tharreau Industries  (THAR FP) rallied 17 percent to 30.3
euros after the non-woven textile company said it plans a one-
time dividend of at least 4 euros a share.  
 Vallourec SA  (VK FP) climbed 3.5 percent to 149.5 euros.
The company has seen a rebound in volumes after a low point
reached in the first quarter, Chairman Philippe Crouzet told La
Tribune in an interview. The company is benefiting from a
recovery in the U.S., Brazil and Asia, while the economy in
Europe is “less good,” Crouzet told the newspaper.  
